Chapter 2: Map the Money Routes
Core Question
Where does money come from, where does it go, and where does it leave?
Understand
Wealth does not begin by accumulating.
Wealth begins by circulating with memory.
A dollar that enters a community can do one job and leave.
Or it can move through several trusted routes before it leaves.
It can pay a member.
That member can buy from a local business.
That business can hire a young person.
That young person can learn a skill.
That skill can support a property project.
That property project can protect a family asset.
That is circulation.
The society must learn how money currently moves.
Where do members spend regularly?
Which expenses repeat?
Which businesses are already trusted?
Which outside systems capture most of the spending?
Which services could be provided locally?
Which costs are emergencies because they were not anticipated?
Money routes reveal beliefs.
Budgets reveal what a community is organized to support.
Discuss
What do members spend money on every month?
Which expenses repeat across many households?
Which businesses already receive our money?
Which businesses could receive more if we organized?
Where does money leave immediately?
What spending could become collective power?
