Chapter 6: Build the Anchor Table
Core Question
Who needs to sit at the table for this pathway to work?
Understand
An ecosystem pathway needs an anchor table.
The anchor table is not a large public meeting.
It is a working group of the people and institutions required to make the pathway real.
For business circulation, the anchor table may include business owners, members, purchasers, youth apprentices, and a recordkeeper.
For property stewardship, it may include property owners, elders, document organizers, trusted professionals, and privacy leads.
For preparedness, it may include care team leads, elders, drivers, medical contacts, and communication coordinators.
For youth formation, it may include mentors, parents, youth, educators, and project leads.
The anchor table should be small enough to work and broad enough to see the pathway clearly.
Discuss
Who must be involved?
Who should be consulted but not placed at the core table?
Who has trust?
Who has technical knowledge?
Who has lived experience?
Who could be harmed if left out?
Who could slow the work if added too early?
