Chapter 8: Create the Communication Route
Core Question
How will people know what to do, where to go, and how to participate?
Understand
An ecosystem fails when information does not move.
People may want to support, but they do not know:
Who to contact
 What is needed
 Where to give
 Where to buy
 Who needs volunteers
 What meeting matters
 What business is part of the campaign
 What documents to bring
 What privacy rules apply
 What action is happening next
A communication route makes participation clear.
It should be simple, repeated, and trustworthy.
Do not rely only on social media.
Use the routes people actually check.
This may include:
Text thread
 Email list
 Church announcements
 Printed flyers
 WhatsApp group
 Simba notifications
 Community bulletin
 Meetings
 Phone tree
 Business counter cards
 Youth messengers
 Elder calls
 Local media
Communication should move people toward action, not just awareness.
Discuss
How do our members actually receive information?
Which communication channels are trusted?
Who is left out if we only use digital tools?
What needs to be private?
What can be public?
Who approves public messages?
Build: Communication Route Plan
Message purpose:

Audience:

Channel:
Text / Email / Simba / Flyer / Meeting / Phone tree / Social media / Local media / Other
Message owner:

Approval needed?
Yes / No
Privacy level:

Call to action:

Repeat schedule:

