Chapter 12: Preparedness Network Project
Core Question
Can we prepare as a network before crisis arrives?
Understand
Preparedness becomes stronger when it is networked.
One household with supplies is useful.
A connected network of households, elders, drivers, caregivers, meeting places, communication routes, and resource lists is stronger.
Preparedness may include:
Communication tree
 Elder check-in network
 Medication needs privacy map
 Ride network
 Emergency supply inventory
 Document backup day
 Power outage plan
 Food and water readiness
 Mutual aid emergency fund
 Neighborhood safety plan
 Evacuation support
 Youth preparedness training
Preparedness is not panic.
Preparedness is care with a calendar.
Discuss
What emergency is most likely?
Who would be most vulnerable?
What communication route would work if power or internet failed?
What supplies are already available?
What care teams should be connected?
What privacy rules must apply?
