Chapter 13: Culture and Creator Ownership Project
Core Question
Can the community own the value of its own genius?
Understand
Culture creates attention, identity, meaning, and markets.
But attention without ownership can become extraction.
A society can help creators, artists, musicians, writers, designers, speakers, and cultural workers protect and circulate value.
This may include:
Creator directory
 Copyright education
 Publishing education
 Licensing awareness
 Community media
 Event ownership
 Venue support
 Creator fund
 Merchandise collaboration
 Archive project
 Youth media training
 Cultural festival with ownership standards
 Contract literacy workshop
The goal is not to reduce culture to money.
The goal is to protect the people who create value from being separated from the value they create.
Who owns the stage?
Who owns the archive?
Who owns the list?
Who owns the rights?
Who gets paid?
Who gets remembered?
Discuss
Who creates cultural value in our community?
Where is that value being captured by others?
What rights or ownership education is needed?
What platform or stage do we control?
What creator support could we organize responsibly?
How do we protect sacred culture from extraction?
